<h1 class="dt__heading1">What is Design Thinking?</h1>
        <p class="dt__paragraph">Design thinking is an approach to understanding problems and developing solutions based on the work of expert designers. Design thinking has been applied to many fields beyond traditional design disciplines. Design thinking emphasizes empathy to better understand user needs, flexible and curious problem exploration, creative generation of potentially innovative concepts, and frequent, iterative development of potential solutions.
        </p>
        <h1 class="dt__heading2">Why is it Important?</h1>
            <p class="dt__paragraph">While design thinking does not perfectly align with traditional course design approaches among engineering faculty, it has been successful because it unlocks new opportunities and can be flexibly adapted to engineering educators' unique approaches and contexts.
                <br><br> Empathy for users promotes deeper engagement with students and enhanced perspectives on the challenges they face that affect their class experience and performance.
                <br> <br> Flexible and curious problem exploration helps identify overlooked issues that can be a better use of one's course design efforts.
                <br> <br> Creative concept generation promotes a greater volume and variety of potentially impactful ideas to incorporate into a course. It's also a lot of fun!
                <br> <br> Frequent, iterative development of course prototypes promotes learning from missteps before it's too late and deeper engagement in the process.
                </p>
                <a id="stagesLink"></a>
                <h1 class="dt__heading1">Stages</h1>
                <p class="dt__paragraph2">
                    Course design thinking can be described as a five-stage process. Each stage serves an important, unique function in the overall process. However, there is frequent iteration and movement between stages. Stages include:
<br> <br> Empathize with students - Develop a better understanding of students' experiences, perspectives, and needs through engagement, observation, connection, and analysis.
<br><br> Define a resonant problem - Develop a specific design problem based on iterative understanding of student needs.
<br><br> Ideate a variety and volume of concepts - Generate many potentially impactful ideas that can inform course changes, especially through conscious effort and visual methods.
<br><br> Prototype course ideas early and often - Develop a variety of prototypes representing portions of a course or course changes to be tested with users.
<br><br> Testing prototypes with students - Share prototypes with students or their proxies to evaluate the effectiveness of addressing the defined problem. This can lead to new insights that refine outcomes in earlier stages.
                </p>
