        </p>
        <h1 class="dt__heading1">What are Mindsets?</h1>
        <p class="dt__paragraph">
            Mindsets are beliefs that orient one's approach or actions. You may be familiar with the growth/fixed mindset. Several other mindsets are particularly relevant to design thinking, typically manifesting as tendencies in your design approach. For example, the empathetic mindset is founded in a belief that understanding and connecting with users is important to the design process and a key part of one's design ethos. This belief orients designers to deeply consider user perspectives and experiences and directly engage them throughout the design process. You may find that some mindsets align better with your beliefs and approaches than others. That's fine! Developing these mindsets is often part of your course design thinking journey. It also helps to work with others who demonstrate mindsets different from your own.
            <a href="/Mindsets.html">See Mindsets Here</a>
        </p>
        <h1 class="dt__heading3">Why Might You Try Course Design Thinking?</h1>
        <p class="dt__paragraph2">
            -- You're having trouble understanding why students do what they do
<br><br> -- You want to improve teaching evaluations
<br><br> -- Students aren't learning what you think they should and you don't know why
<br><br> -- You have something you want to try out in your course but you can't figure out how
<br><br> -- You're new to teaching or course development and you want some guidance
<br><br> -- You're a veteran course designer but you feel your methods becoming stale
        </p>
